I just had an awful experience with Reunion. I order for them all the time. Today they forgot to give my Uber Eats driver my main order (chicken shawarma). I called the restaurant kindly and the manager (male) and explained. He then told me (I had to call him back) said they cannot refund me, cannot send me a new order via another driver and instead asked me to call Uber Eats and figure it out. The food is great, the manager is completely rude and unhelpful. In the end I suggested he give me a free order of the dish (because I won’t get it tonight) and he said “I will leave a note” and hung up. If your fine with someone who is unkind and unhelpful in this world then go ahead and try Reunion because the food is good. I won’t bother picking up my food because I’m embarrassed on how badly I was helped. I don’t really write reviews but felt compelled to do so - as I am a loyal customer there and have always recommended it.

Food was decent but not authentic in the slightest aside from the fluffy pita. We ordered: -hummus: the viscosity was too liquidy but the flavor was fine. Very small portion. -falafel: 3 oblong balls of falafel (most places usually it comes with at least 4), flavor was decent. -yemenite pancake: one piece of 10 inch malawach pastry. Probably one of the best dishes we had tonight. However, it was literally one flat piece of pastry, so I don't understand how it's considered a main entree and under the same category as their shakshuka, shawarma, and other mains...would put this under the appetizers. -incredible shawarma: chicken shawarma and potatoes. Really nothing special here. -moroccan tacos: two "tacos" with the base made from pita bread, filled with a piece of sausage and some veggies. Spicy. Average. -knafeh: good flavor and good portions, but it's way too soft. Good knafeh is supposed to be crunch on the top and bottom, this wasn't it. -cheesecake krembo: not sure where the cheesecake part was, maybe they forgot it.  If you're looking for appetizer portions of inauthentic Israeli food, this is the place. If you're looking for real Israeli food you can find in Israel, skip it.

This is a great place for brunch - a Williamsburg special indeed. However be ready to wait upto 30 minutes if you go without a reservation on a weekend. You have the option to eat inside or outside. It’s pretty cosy and well decorated but slightly cramped for space as I did feel very conscious of my elbows as people tried to move through the tiny strip of space between my table and the next one.  Coming to the food - it was delicious, fresh and healthy. We got the Shakshooka (minus any toppings) which everyone else also seemed to be getting. This was really delicious and served with a medium slice of Challah (braided) bread. My only gripe was the bread was not enough for the egg dish. They should have given atleast two servings of bread for the price.  We also got the Shibak platter which included the following:  1. Some slices of toasted pita bread 2. Soft boiled egg 3. Deep fried eggplant poppers 4. Mango and tahini sauce  Everything was delicious. But one thing to note is that the portion sizes are on the smaller side. So if you want a hearty brunch, you’ll have to order a few additional items. The focus is on healthy eating I guess.  All in all a happening cozy brunch place with a chill vibe and great service. Will be back for lunch or dinner.  The meat was kosher, not halal.
